#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:10
msgid "4.1 The Classic Boltzmann Machine: Visible and Hidden Symmetry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:12
msgid ""
"The preceding chapters have built the theoretical foundations—statistical"
" physics, recurrent neural dynamics, and energy-based learning, that "
"culminate in the **Boltzmann machine**. In this section, we present the "
"architecture of the classic, fully connected Boltzmann machine as "
"originally proposed by Geoffrey Hinton and Terrence Sejnowski in 1985. We"
" will examine its structure, its probabilistic semantics, the learning "
"algorithm that shapes its energy landscape, and the practical limitations"
" that motivated the development of restricted variants."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:14
msgid "The Architecture: A Fully Connected Stochastic Network"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:15
msgid ""
"A classic Boltzmann machine is a recurrent neural network composed of "
"**stochastic binary units**. Each unit $x_i$ can be in one of two states:"
" active (1) or inactive (0). The units are partitioned into two sets:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:17
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"**Visible units** $\\mathbf{v} \\in \\{0,1\\}^{N_v}$: These interface "
"with the external world. They receive data during training and represent "
"the observed variables of interest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:18
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"**Hidden units** $\\mathbf{h} \\in \\{0,1\\}^{N_h}$: These are internal, "
"latent variables that capture higher-order structure and dependencies not"
" directly observed in the visible data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:20
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Crucially, the classic Boltzmann machine is **fully connected**: every "
"unit is symmetrically connected to every other unit, regardless of "
"whether they are visible or hidden. The weight matrix $\\mathbf{W}$ is a "
"square, symmetric matrix of size $N \\times N$, where $N = N_v + N_h$. "
"The symmetry condition,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:22
#, python-brace-format
msgid "w_{ij} = w_{ji}, \\quad \\text{for all } i, j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:24
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"is essential because it guarantees the existence of a well-defined energy"
" function and ensures that the stochastic dynamics converge to an "
"equilibrium distribution. Self-connections are prohibited (\\( w_{ii} = 0"
" \\)), as they would merely add a constant offset to the energy without "
"affecting the conditional distributions that drive sampling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:26
msgid ""
"Each unit also has a **bias** $b_i$, which can be interpreted as a "
"connection from an always-active unit or as an external field acting on "
"that unit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:28
msgid "The Energy Function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:29
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The energy of a joint configuration $(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h})$ is "
"defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:31
msgid ""
"E(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}) = -\\sum_{i \\in \\text{vis}} b_i v_i - "
"\\sum_{j \\in \\text{hid}} c_j h_j - \\sum_{i<j} w_{ij} x_i x_j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:33
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $\\mathbf{x} = (\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h})$ denotes the full state "
"vector, $b_i$ are visible biases, and $c_j$ are hidden biases. The "
"summation over $i<j$ runs over all distinct pairs of units, both visible-"
"visible, visible-hidden, and hidden-hidden."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:35
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"This energy function defines a joint probability distribution over all "
"$2^{N}$ possible states via the Boltzmann distribution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:37
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h}) = \\frac{1}{Z} \\exp\\left(-E(\\mathbf{v}, "
"\\mathbf{h})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:39
msgid "where the partition function $Z$ sums over all joint configurations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:41
msgid ""
"Z = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}, \\tilde{\\mathbf{h}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-E(\\tilde{\\mathbf{v}}, \\tilde{\\mathbf{h}})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:43
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The probability of observing a visible vector $\\mathbf{v}$ alone is "
"obtained by marginalizing over the hidden units:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:45
msgid ""
"P(\\mathbf{v}) = \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{h}}} P(\\mathbf{v}, "
"\\tilde{\\mathbf{h}}) = \\frac{1}{Z} \\sum_{\\tilde{\\mathbf{h}}} "
"\\exp\\left(-E(\\mathbf{v}, \\tilde{\\mathbf{h}})\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:47
msgid "Stochastic Dynamics and Equilibrium"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:48
msgid ""
"The network operates as a **stochastic dynamical system**. At each time "
"step, a unit is selected at random, and its new state is sampled from its"
" conditional distribution given the states of all other units. For a unit"
" $i$, the probability of being active is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:50
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"P(x_i = 1 \\mid \\mathbf{x}_{-i}) = \\sigma\\left( \\sum_{j \\neq i} "
"w_{ij} x_j + b_i \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:52
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $\\sigma(z) = 1/(1 + \\exp(-z))$ is sigmoid function, and "
"$\\mathbf{x}_{-i}$ denotes the states of all units except $i$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:54
msgid ""
"Because the weights are symmetric, this update satisfies detailed balance"
" with respect to the Boltzmann distribution defined in Section [1.2 The "
"Boltzmann Distribution and Equilibrium](kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-"
"boltzmann.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:56
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Consequently, if the network is allowed to run for a sufficiently long "
"time (i.e., many asynchronous updates), the sequence of states "
"constitutes a Markov chain whose stationary distribution is exactly "
"$P(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h})$. This property is the cornerstone of both "
"inference and learning in the Boltzmann machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:58
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Consequently, repeated application drives the network toward equilibrium,"
" where configurations are sampled according to $P(\\mathbf{v}, "
"\\mathbf{h})$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:60
msgid "Learning Objective: Maximum Likelihood with Hidden Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:61
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The goal of learning is to adjust the weights and biases so that the "
"marginal distribution over visible units, $P(\\mathbf{v})$, approximates "
"the empirical distribution of the training data. As derived in Section "
"[3.1 Defining the Objective: Low Energy for Real Data](kpp-theoretical-"
"foundations-ebms-def.md), the gradient of the negative log-likelihood for"
" a single training example $\\mathbf{v}$ with respect to a weight "
"$w_{ij}$ is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:63
msgid ""
"\\frac{\\partial \\left( -\\log P(\\mathbf{v}) \\right)}{\\partial "
"w_{ij}} = \\mathbb{E}_{\\mathbf{h} \\mid \\mathbf{v}} \\left[ x_i x_j "
"\\right] - \\mathbb{E}_{P(\\mathbf{v}, \\mathbf{h})} \\left[ x_i x_j "
"\\right]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:65
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Here, $ x_i$ and $x_j$ denote the states of the two connected units. The "
"first term is the expected product of their activities when the visible "
"units are **clamped** to the training example $\\mathbf{v}$ and the "
"hidden units are allowed to fluctuate according to their conditional "
"distribution. This is the **positive phase** or **wake phase** statistic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:67
msgid ""
"The second term is the expected product when the network runs **freely** "
"without any external input, sampling from its equilibrium distribution. "
"This is the **negative phase** or **sleep phase** statistic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:69
msgid "The learning rule is thus:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:71
msgid ""
"\\Delta w_{ij} = \\eta \\left( \\langle x_i x_j "
"\\rangle_{\\text{clamped}} - \\langle x_i x_j \\rangle_{\\text{free}} "
"\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:73
msgid ""
"where $\\eta$ is the learning rate. Biases are updated similarly by "
"treating them as weights from an always-on unit with state 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:75
msgid "The Wake-Sleep Algorithm: A Biological Metaphor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:76
msgid ""
"The two-phase nature of the learning rule suggests a compelling "
"biological metaphor. In the **wake phase**, the network is driven by "
"sensory input (the visible units are clamped to data). The hidden units "
"respond to this input, and the correlations $\\langle x_i x_j "
"\\rangle_{\\text{clamped}}$ are recorded. These correlations strengthen "
"connections between units that tend to be co-active in response to real-"
"world stimuli—a Hebbian process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:78
msgid ""
"In the **sleep phase**, the network is disconnected from sensory input "
"and generates its own \"fantasies\" by running freely from its "
"equilibrium distribution. The correlations $\\langle x_i x_j "
"\\rangle_{\\text{free}}$ recorded during this phase are used to weaken "
"connections that are spuriously co-active in the model's internal "
"fantasies—an anti-Hebbian process that prevents the network from "
"generating patterns not present in the data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:80
msgid ""
"The difference between the wake and sleep statistics drives learning. "
"This **contrastive Hebbian learning** elegantly combines local synaptic "
"updates with a global objective."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:82
msgid "The Computational Bottleneck: Equilibrium Sampling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:83
msgid ""
"Despite its theoretical elegance, the classic Boltzmann machine suffers "
"from a severe practical limitation: **the need to sample from the "
"equilibrium distribution in both phases is computationally prohibitive**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:85
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"In the clamped phase, we must sample hidden states from $P(\\mathbf{h} "
"\\mid \\mathbf{v})$. Because the hidden units are fully connected to one "
"another, they do not become conditionally independent given the visible "
"units. Computing the exact conditional distribution requires summing over"
" all $2^{N_h}$ hidden configurations, which is intractable for non-"
"trivial $N_h$. Instead, we must run a Markov chain over the hidden units "
"until it reaches equilibrium—a process that can be extremely slow, "
"especially when the energy landscape has high barriers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:87
msgid ""
"In the free phase, the situation is even worse: we must run a Markov "
"chain over **all** $N$ units until the joint distribution reaches "
"equilibrium. The mixing time of this chain scales poorly with network "
"size, and for large networks, obtaining unbiased samples is effectively "
"impossible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:89
msgid "The Unconstrained Connectivity: A Double-Edged Sword"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:90
msgid ""
"The fully connected architecture gives the classic Boltzmann machine its "
"theoretical power: it is a **universal approximator** for probability "
"distributions over binary vectors, given enough hidden units. The hidden-"
"hidden connections allow the model to capture complex, higher-order "
"dependencies that simpler models miss."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:92
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"However, this same connectivity is the source of the computational "
"intractability. The hidden units are not conditionally independent given "
"the visible units, nor are the visible units conditionally independent "
"given the hidden units. Every sampling step requires computing the total "
"input to a unit from **all** other units, visible and hidden alike, and "
"the Markov chain must mix over a state space of size $2^{N}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:94
msgid ""
"In practice, training a classic Boltzmann machine on anything but tiny "
"toy problems was infeasible with 1980s and 1990s computing resources. The"
" algorithm remained a theoretical curiosity until the introduction of "
"architectural restrictions that dramatically simplified the sampling "
"process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:96
msgid "The Path Forward: Restricted Architectures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:97
msgid ""
"The limitations of the classic Boltzmann machine motivated a crucial "
"architectural innovation: the **Restricted Boltzmann Machine (RBM)**. By "
"removing all visible-visible and hidden-hidden connections, the RBM makes"
" the units in one layer conditionally independent given the other layer. "
"This seemingly small change has profound computational consequences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:99
msgid ""
"**Clamped phase sampling**: Given visible units, the hidden units become "
"independent, and their states can be sampled in parallel in a single "
"step. No Markov chain is needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:100
msgid ""
"**Free phase sampling**: Block Gibbs sampling alternates between updating"
" all hidden units given the visible units and all visible units given the"
" hidden units. While still requiring multiple iterations to reach "
"equilibrium, each iteration is fast and parallelizable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:102
msgid ""
"The RBM, combined with the **contrastive divergence** approximation "
"(Section [3.3 Contrastive Divergence](kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-"
"cd.md)), transformed the Boltzmann machine from a theoretical construct "
"into a practical tool for unsupervised feature learning. The classic "
"Boltzmann machine thus serves as the conceptual foundation, the "
"\"Platonic ideal\", from which more tractable variants are derived."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:104
msgid "Recap: The Classic Boltzmann Machine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:105
msgid ""
"The classic Boltzmann machine embodies the core principles of energy-"
"based generative modeling:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:107
msgid ""
"**Architecture**: A fully connected, symmetric recurrent network of "
"stochastic binary units, partitioned into visible and hidden sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:108
msgid ""
"**Energy function**: A quadratic form over all units, with weights and "
"biases as parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:109
msgid ""
"**Dynamics**: Asynchronous stochastic updates that converge to the "
"Boltzmann equilibrium distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:110
msgid ""
"**Learning**: Contrastive Hebbian updates driven by the difference "
"between clamped (wake) and free-running (sleep) correlations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:111
msgid ""
"**Limitation**: The need for equilibrium sampling over a fully connected "
"graph renders exact training computationally intractable for all but the "
"smallest networks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:113
msgid ""
"The next section introduces the **Restricted Boltzmann Machine**, which "
"imposes structural constraints that dramatically reduce sampling "
"complexity while retaining much of the expressive power of the classic "
"model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:115
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:116
msgid ""
"The **classic Boltzmann machine** is a fully connected, undirected "
"probabilistic graphical model with symmetric weights and stochastic "
"binary units."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:117
msgid ""
"Units are divided into **visible** (observed data) and **hidden** (latent"
" features) groups, with full connectivity among all units."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:118
msgid ""
"The energy function defines a joint Boltzmann distribution, and "
"stochastic updates guarantee convergence to equilibrium."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:119
msgid ""
"Learning follows a **contrastive Hebbian rule**: increase weights based "
"on correlations when visible units are clamped to data, and decrease "
"weights based on correlations when the network runs freely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:120
msgid ""
"The fully connected architecture makes **exact inference and equilibrium "
"sampling intractable**, limiting practical applications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-bm-overall.md:121
msgid ""
"The computational bottleneck of the classic Boltzmann machine motivated "
"the development of the **Restricted Boltzmann Machine (RBM)**, which "
"removes certain connections to enable efficient sampling."
msgstr ""

